Clustering on Project Completion Reports

Arthur Charpentier and Ewen Gallic

2020-10-03

1 Data Cleaning

1.1 Loading Data

Two types of project completion reports are considered:

  • the reports made by the beneficiaries of the allowances (project completion reports, or PCR)
  • reports produced internally by IFAD (project completion reports validation, or PCRV)

For the PCR, the following information is available:

  • the report in PDF format
  • the extraction of the text content (for old or digitally copied reports, a character recognition has been previously performed outside this work)
  • metadata.

For the PCRV, only the metadata is available.

1.1.1 Project Completion Reports (PCRs)

Note: the R codes of this subsection are also available in the file 01_extract_text.R.

1.1.1.2 Extraction of Text

Each project involves the completion of multiple reports:

  • PDR: design report
  • MTR: mid-term report
  • PSR: supervision report
  • PCR: project completions report

Our focus here is on PCRs. The corpus of all reports have already been extracted from the PDF reports. They have been saved in a CSV file. Each row of the dataset gives the text extracted from a single page of a report. The columns of the dataset are as follows:

Name Type Description
Country character the country where the project was funded
ID character the unique identifier of the report
Type of report character the type of report (PDR, MTR, PCR, PSR, see below for details)
Page double page number
File_name character name of the PDF report
text character extracted text

The data can be loaded into the R session using the code below:

reports <- 
  read_delim("03_Cornell_input_Phase01.csv",
             col_types = 
               cols(
                 Country = col_character(),
                 ID = col_character(),
                 `Type of report` = col_character(),
                 Page = col_double(),
                 File_name = col_character(),
                 text = col_character()
               ),
             delim = ";")

We focus on the PCRs:

completion_reports <- 
  reports %>% 
  filter(`Type of report` == "PCR")

Completion reports contain a section on lessons learned during the project. The content of this section is subject to statistical analysis. It is therefore important to extract the text of this section properly. Unfortunately, the diversity of documents, the lack of compliance with standards and the presence of some documents in image rather than text format make this task difficult to be automated. As a first step, we wanted to automatically extract the section typically titled “Lessons Learned” from the texts. This task proved impossible for several reasons that we detail here.

Our initial approach was simple: locate the beginning of the “Lessons Learned” section, then locate the end of the section. This last task is not straightforward: sometimes it is the final section, but sometimes it is followed by a “Conclusion” section. Most of the time, it is followed by an appendix, which is not easy to recognize. An attempt has been made to locate the numbering of the sections, but again, the diversity in the documents complicates the task (Roman numerals, Arabic numerals, letters); besides, the problem regarding the presence or absence of a subsequent section occurs again.

The capacity of the algorithm developed to perform the extraction being far from satisfactory (at most, about fifty documents processed), we opted for a more tedious but safer method: the manual retrieval of the paragraphs to be imported. For each document, we write down in a table the page in which the “Lessons Learned” section begins and the page in which it ends. We also add the beginning of the first paragraph of that section and the last words.

The following code prepares the empty table that needs to be manually filled:

completion_reports %>% 
  filter(ID %in% df_completion_ratings$`Project Id`) %>% 
  group_by(ID) %>% 
  slice(1) %>% 
  select(ID, File_name) %>% 
  mutate(tmp = str_c('"', ID, '", "', File_name, '", "", "", "","",\n')) %>% 
  .$tmp %>% 
  cat()

Each row of this table should contain:

  • the report identifier
  • the name of one of the pages (used to find your way around when searching for files manually, then unused)
  • the start page of the “Lessons Learned” section identified manually
  • the end page of the “Lessons Learned” section identified manually
  • the first words of the section
  • the last words of the section

For a better understanding, here is an illustrative example for the report whose identifier is 1100001662. This report concerns a project in Vietnam. The PDF file is named vietnam_1100001662_completion-report.pdf. We see that the “Lessons Learned” section runs from page 53 to 54. The first sentence of the section starts with the following string: The SRDP implementation has actually been. It ends with: CSA and PPP investments. Thus, the table we create will contain the following row:

c("1100001662", "vietnam_1100001662_completion-report.pdf.content1",
  "53", "54", "The SRDP implementation has actually been","CSA and PPP investments")

This vector is then transformed into a table:

table_infos_example <- 
  c("1100001662", "vietnam_1100001662_completion-report.pdf.content1",
  "53", "54", "The SRDP implementation has actually been","CSA and PPP investments") %>% 
  matrix(ncol = 6, byrow = TRUE) %>% 
  as_tibble() %>% 
  magrittr::set_colnames(c("ID", "File_name", "start_page", "end_page", "start_text", "end_text"))

Next, we use a function that fetches from pages 53 to 54 the part of the text that starts with The SRDP implementation has actually been and ends with CSA and PPP investments.

#' extract_lessons_learned
#' Extracts the "Lessons Learned" part from document whose information is contained in row `i` from `table_infos`
#' @param i (integer) the ith row of `table_infos`
#' @param table_infos table that contains the ID of the report, the start and end pages of the "Lessons Learned" section, the beginning and the end words of the same section.
extract_lessons_learned <- function(i, table_infos){
  
  # Focus on the ith row
  pcr_lessons_learned_pages_curr <- table_infos %>% slice(i)
  
  # The pages to extract
  pages_to_extract <- seq(pcr_lessons_learned_pages_curr$start_page, pcr_lessons_learned_pages_curr$end_page)
  
  # Patterns of the start and end of the text to extract
  pattern_start <- pcr_lessons_learned_pages_curr$start_text
  pattern_end <- pcr_lessons_learned_pages_curr$end_text
  
  # Raw text from the PCR
  raw_text <- 
    completion_reports %>% 
    filter(ID == pcr_lessons_learned_pages_curr$ID) %>% 
    filter(Page %in% pages_to_extract) %>% 
    magrittr::extract2("text") %>% 
    str_c(collapse = "\n")
  
  # Trying to locate the start and end of the subtring to extract (positions in `raw_text`)
  # (we keep the first that occurs for the start of Lessons Learned)
  start_pos <- str_locate_all(raw_text, pattern_start) %>% magrittr::extract2(1)
  start_pos <- start_pos[, "start"] %>% first()
  # (we keep the last that occurs for the end of Lessons Learned)
  end_pos <- str_locate_all(raw_text, pattern_end) %>% magrittr::extract2(1)
  end_pos <- end_pos[, "end"] %>% last()
  
  # Extracting text
  text_res <- str_sub(raw_text, start = start_pos, end = end_pos)
  
  # Putting the result in a tibble and returning it
  tibble(ID = pcr_lessons_learned_pages_curr$ID, lessons_learned = text_res, start_pos = start_pos, end_pos = end_pos)
}# End of extract_lessons_learned()

Then, we just have to apply this function to the table containing the extraction instructions.

extract_lessons_learned(i=1, table_infos = table_infos_example)

1.1.2 Project Completion Reports Validation (PCRVs)

In addition to the reports produced at the completion of the projects by the grant recipients, some projects are evaluated objectively by IFAD and result in the production of other documents called “Project Completion Reports Validation” (PCRVs). These reports, unlike the RCPs presented previously, are standardized. It is therefore much easier to automatically extract information from the the PDF files.

Note: the R codes of this subsection are also available in the file 01_PCRV.R.

1.1.2.1 Downloading the Reports

The PCRVs can be downloaded directly from the IFAD website at the following address:: https://www.ifad.org/en/web/ioe/pcrv. To access them, the country in which the project took place must first be selected. The following piece of code will bring up the list of countries:

library(rvest, eval=FALSE)
# Extract the list of countries to parse
start_page <- read_html("https://www.ifad.org/en/web/ioe/pcrv")

# Years do not seem important to get all the results. We shall then skip those and just focus on the countries.
countries <- 
  start_page %>% 
  html_nodes("select#Country-field")

countries_df <- 
  map_df(countries, function(x){
    id <- 
      x %>% 
      html_nodes("option") %>% 
      rvest::html_attr(name = "value")
    
    name <- 
      x %>% 
      html_nodes("option") %>% 
      html_text(trim = TRUE)
    
    countries_df <-
      tibble(id = id, name = name)
  }) %>% 
  filter(str_length(id) > 0)

countries_df
load("../data/PCRV/countries_df.rda")
print(countries_df)

The list of these countries, and especially their corresponding identifier, is then used to define the url of the page listing the available reports for a given country. For example, for Afghanistan, whose ID on the IFAD website is 40973882 (as obtained from the countries_df table), we retrieve the contents of the page whose URL is https://www.ifad.org/en/web/ioe/pcrv?mode=search&catCountry=40973882. In this page, we retrieve all the report titles listed as well as the links to the files.

For convenience, we create a function that takes a line number from countries_df as input, retrieves the country identifier from the ith line, and then tries to return the links listed for the ith country.

#' get_reports_pages_url
#' Extract the urls for the project evaluations of a given country
#' @param i ith row of `countries_df`
get_reports_pages_url <- function(i){
  country_curr <- countries_df %>% slice(i)
  # country_curr <- 
  #   countries_df %>% filter(name == "China")
  
  # Form the URL
  url_curr <- 
    str_c("https://www.ifad.org/en/web/ioe/pcrv?mode=search&catCountry=", country_curr$id)
  
  # Extract the content
  page_projects_curr <- read_html(url_curr)
  
  projects <- 
    page_projects_curr %>% 
    html_nodes("div.row-fluid.related-row")
  
  res <- 
    map_df(projects, function(x){
      urls <- 
        x %>% 
        html_nodes("div.related-row-title a") %>% 
        html_attr(name = "href")
      urls
     
      titles <- 
        x %>% 
        html_nodes("div.related-row-title a") %>% 
        html_text()
      
      years <-
        x %>% 
        html_nodes("span.abstract-category:contains('YEAR')") %>% 
        html_text() %>% 
        str_remove("YEAR: ") %>% 
        str_trim()
      
      tibble(
        country = country_curr$name,
        country_id = country_curr$id,
        year = years,
        title = titles,
        url = urls)
    })
  
  res
}

Then, we just have to loop on the indices of the countries_df table to get all the links to the PDFs of the PCRVs.

urls_reports_df <- NULL
for(i in 1:nrow(countries_df)){
  urls_reports_df_tmp <- get_reports_pages_url(i)
  urls_reports_df <-
    urls_reports_df %>% 
    bind_rows(urls_reports_df_tmp)
}

1.1.2.2 Matching with Metainformation

As with completion reports, validation reports result in the creation of indicators. These are provided in an Excel file:

df_external_ratings_all_pcrv <- 
  read_excel("../data/external_ratings_IOE data series 27May20.xlsx", sheet = "All PCRV-PPE", skip = 4) %>% 
  mutate(`Project ID` = str_c("110000", `Project ID`))

Unfortunately, the files uploaded to the IFAD website do not mention the project identification number. Therefore, we cannot directly match the PDF files to the metadata. We will perform a join based on the project title, the country and the year. There are three minor problems. First, the names of the countries listed on the IFAD website sometimes differ from the names of the countries in the Excel file. Some manual adjustments are required to match the two data sources. Second, the titles may be slightly different depending on the source (some words may be added on the titles shown on the website relative to the titles from the Excel file). Third, the year displayed on the website mostly refers to the completion one, but it may sometimes differ.

The first issue can easily be tackled, by manually correcting the names of the countries:

urls_reports_df <- 
  urls_reports_df %>% 
  mutate(country = ifelse(country == "Bosnia and Herzegovina", yes = "Bosnia", no = country)) %>% 
  mutate(country = ifelse(country == "Lao People's Democratic Republic", yes = "Laos", no = country)) %>% 
  mutate(country = ifelse(country == "Viet Nam", yes = "Vietnam", no = country)) %>% 
  mutate(country = ifelse(country == "Bolivia (Plurinational State of)", yes = "Bolivia", no = country)) %>% 
  mutate(country = ifelse(country == "Côte d'Ivoire", yes = "Cote d'Ivoire", no = country)) %>% 
  mutate(country = ifelse(country == "Democratic Republic of the Congo", yes = "DR Congo", no = country)) %>% 
  mutate(country = ifelse(country == "Gambia The", yes = "Gambia", no = country)) %>% 
  mutate(title = ifelse(title == "Project for Reviving Food Crops and Small Livestock Production in the Savannah", yes ="Project to Revitalize Crop and Livestock Production in the Savannah", no = title))

To address the second issue, we will remove all punctuation and spaces from the titles in the title of both sources and turn the string to lowercase. Then, using the stringdist() function from the package {stringdist}, we can assess the Damerau-Levenshtein distance from two strings to try to perform partial matches between the titles.

library(stringdist)
## 
## Attaching package: 'stringdist'
## The following object is masked from 'package:tidyr':
## 
##     extract
#' clean_title
# removes punctuation and spaces from the titles, as well as texts contained between brackets
#' @param x string
clean_title <- function(x){
  x %>% str_remove_all("\\(.*\\)$") %>% 
    str_trim() %>% 
    # word(start = 1, end = 4) %>% 
    str_remove_all("[[:punct:]]|[[:space:]]") %>% 
    str_to_lower()
}

For the third issue, we will consider an interval of 1 year prior and 1 year posterior the reported date on IFAD’s website to be able to match the two sources.

Once again, we created a function to try to perform those tasks for a single observation. This function considers the ith row of the metadata and tries to find a match within the reports downloaded from the Internet. If a match is found, the ID previously created is returned.

#' add_project_id
#' Add the ID of the project as defined in `01_project_eval.R`
#' @param i ith row of df_external_ratings_all_pcrv for which we want to get the ID defined from the reports downloaded
add_project_id <- function(i){
  
  # Focus on ith row of the metadata
  df_external_ratings_all_eval_curr <- 
    df_external_ratings_all_pcrv %>% slice(i)
  
  # Remove punctuation and spaces from countries names
  # Keeping the files from IFAD's website where the country and year matches the ith row of the metadata
  urls_reports_df_curr <- 
    urls_reports_df %>% 
    filter(clean_title(country) == clean_title(df_external_ratings_all_eval_curr$Country),
           year %in% seq(df_external_ratings_all_eval_curr$`Evaluation year`-1, df_external_ratings_all_eval_curr$`Evaluation year`+1))
  
  # Extracting the titles of the reports from the medatada and from IFAD's website
  title_cleaned <- clean_title(df_external_ratings_all_eval_curr$Project)
  clean_potential <- clean_title(urls_reports_df_curr$title)
  
  # Damerau-Levenshtein distance between these titles
  dist <- stringdist::stringdist(title_cleaned, clean_potential)
  
  # Expressed as a percentage of the longest string length
  dist_pct <- dist / map_dbl(clean_potential, function(x) max(str_length(title_cleaned), str_length(x)))
  
  # Keeping the ID of the matched report from IFAD's website
  project_report_id <- 
    urls_reports_df_curr %>% 
    mutate(dist_pct = dist_pct) %>% 
    filter(dist_pct < .2) %>% 
    arrange(dist_pct) %>% 
    slice(1) %>% 
    magrittr::extract2("id_PCRV")
  
  project_report_id <- ifelse(length(project_report_id) == 0, yes = NA, no = project_report_id)
  
  project_report_id
}# End of add_project_id()

1.1.2.3 Extraction of the Information from the PDF Files

The PDFs downloaded from the IFAD’s website contain a section giving the lessons learned. Unlike the Project Completion Reports, the validation reports are almost normalized (the norms may change over the years).

We extracted these sections from the PDFs, using the {pdftools} package.

Let us focus on the reports for which a match was found in the metadata.

library(pdftools)
## Using poppler version 0.73.0
ll <- ids[!is.na(ids)]

Then, let us create a function that opens a PDF file depending on its ID and then returns the text content. This function returns a list whose elements are the pages of the file.

import_pdf <- function(l){
  report_pdf <- pdftools::pdf_text(pdf = str_c("../data/PCRV/", l, ".pdf"))
  report_pdf
}

A loop over all the IDs is performed. At each iteration, the import_pdf() function is applied.

reports_pdf <- map(ll, import_pdf)
names(reports_pdf) <- ll

Then, we need to extract the “Lessons Learned” part from the content of each file. To that end, we create two functions. The main one, extract_lessons() takes an integer i as input. It gets the ith element of the texts contained in the list reports_pdf previously obtained. Then, it tries to extract the “Lessons Learned” section. The second function, extract_lessons_help() is specifically designed to extract a substring from a string (f), given the number of the page in which the section “Lessons Learned” was spotted (beg), given the start and end patterns to look for to locate the section of interest (start_pattern and end_pattern, resp.).

#' extract_lessons_help
#' @param f string
#' @param beg page in which the start of the section "Lessons Learned" was spotted
#' @param start_pattern regex that gives the pattern to look for to define the beginning of the section
#' @param end_patternregex that gives the pattern to look for to define the end of the section
extract_lessons_help <- function(f, beg, start_pattern, end_pattern){
  end <- which(str_detect(f, end_pattern))
  text <- NA
  if(length(end)>0){
    if(length(end)>1) stop("Problem")
    text_pages <- f[seq(beg, end)] %>% str_c(collapse = "\n")
    
    pos_beg <- str_locate(string = text_pages, pattern = start_pattern)[1,"end"]
    pos_end <- str_locate(string = text_pages, pattern = end_pattern)[1, "start"]
    
    text <- str_sub(text_pages, start = pos_beg, end = pos_end)
    
  }
  list(beg = beg, end = end, text = text)
}

The “Lessons Learned” section is usually defined as “Lessons Learned” (sometimes with capital letters for the first letters of the worlds). It always appears as the fifth section. The numbering is either in roman numbers or in letters. We can use this information to try to locate the start of that section in the documents. To identify where the section ends, we can use the fact that the subsequent section is either “Definition and rating of the evaluation”, or “Rating comparison”, or “Issues for IOE follow-up” for most documents. For the reports from 2015 and 2016, there is no “Section Learned” section. However, the reports from those years have a section names “Assessment of PCR quality” followed by another one named either “Candour” or “Lessons”, or “Lessons learned”.

extract_lessons <- function(i){
  
  f <- reports_pdf[[i]]
  
  patterns <- c("V\\.[[:space:]]*Lessons (l|L)earn(ed|t)",
               "V\\.[[:space:]]*Final (r|R)emarks and (l|L)essons (l|L)earned",
               "V\\.[[:space:]]*Final (r|R)emarks",
               "E\\.[[:space:]]*(1)?[[:space:]]*Lessons (l|L)earn(ed|t)",
               "E\\.[[:space:]]*Learning (t|T)opics")
  
  pattern <- patterns %>%
    str_c(collapse = "|")
  
  end <- text <- NA
  beg <- which(str_detect(f, pattern))
  
  if(length(beg)>0){
    tmp <- extract_lessons_help(f = f, beg = beg,
                                start_pattern = pattern, end_pattern = "Definition and rating of the evaluation")
    text <- tmp$text
    if(is.na(text)){
      tmp <- extract_lessons_help(f = f, beg = beg,
                                  start_pattern = pattern, end_pattern = "Rating (c|C)omparison\n")
      text <- tmp$text
    }
    if(is.na(text)){
      tmp <- extract_lessons_help(f = f, beg = beg,
                                  start_pattern = pattern, end_pattern = "(E|F)\\.(2?)[[:space:]]*Issues for IOE (f|F)ollow-up")
      text <- tmp$text
    }
    if(is.na(text)){
      tmp <- extract_lessons_help(f = f, beg = beg,
                                  start_pattern = pattern, end_pattern = "(F|G)\\.[[:space:]]*Rating Comparisons")
      text <- tmp$text
    }
    
    
    end <- tmp$end
  }else{
    # For reports completed in 2015 and 2016
    patterns <- c("(III|IV)\\.[[:space:]]*Assessment of PCR (q|Q)uality")
    
    pattern <- patterns %>%
      str_c(collapse = "|")
    
    beg <- which(str_detect(f, pattern))
    
    
    if(length(beg)>0){
      tmp <- extract_lessons_help(f = f, beg = beg,
                                  start_pattern = pattern, end_pattern = "[[:space:]]Candour(\n|\\.[[:space:]])")
      
      if(!is.na(tmp$text)){
        # Keep only the Lessons learned part
        tmp$text <- str_sub(tmp$text, start = str_locate(tmp$text, "[[:space:]]Lessons( learned)?(\n|\\.[[:space:]])")[1,"end"])
        text <- tmp$text
      }
      
      
      end <- tmp$end
    }
    
  }
  
  if(length(beg) == 0) beg <- NA
  
  
  res <- tibble(beg = beg, end = end, id_PCRV = ll[i], text = text)
  res
}# End of extract_lessons()

We loop over the rows of reports_pdf and apply the extract_lessons() function at each iteration.

lessons_learned_df <- NULL
for(i in 1:length(reports_pdf)) {
  lessons_learned_df <- lessons_learned_df %>% bind_rows(extract_lessons(i))
}

1.2 Translation

Some reports are written in Spanish, others in French. If we want to integrate these documents into the analysis, one of the ways to do so is to translate them into English. We can use Google’s API, called Cloud Translation. Cloud Translation allows 500,000 characters to be translated for free every day (every 24 hours).

Several products are available (API Translation Basic, API Translation Advanced, AutoML Translation and API Media Translation. For what we need to do, i.e., translating a few pages, the basic solution is more than enough. It should be noted that if more texts were to be translated, Google charges $20 per million characters (for queries between 500,000 and 1 billion characters) and offers customizable price plans beyond 1 billion characters.

To be able to translate the Spanish and French “Lessons Learned” parts of the extracted texts using the Cloud Translation API, the first step is to create a Google account (if you already have one, you can use it). Then, the second step consists in adding a payment method (be careful with that, it may be a good idea to link a virtual card with a low amount of money on it: some APIs can be quite expensive with Google!). This step is mandatory, even though the first 500,000 characters are free of charge. The third step consists in creating a virtual project and getting some credentials for it. These credentials can then be stored in a JSON file that can be passed on the the R function gl_auth() from {googleLanguageR}. More details on the procedure are provided on this vignette titled “How to get your own API credentials”.

Once the credentials are stored in a JSON file, the only thing to do is to authenticate with Google Cloud Translation API using the following code:

library(tidyverse)
library(rvest)
library(googleLanguageR)

path_to_json_creds <- "path_to_your_json_file.json"
gl_auth(json_file = path_to_json_creds)

The texts can then be translated with the following function:

test <- googleLanguageR::gl_translate("Bonjour tout le monde", source = "fr", target = "en", format = "text")
test

The arguments source and target are used to specify the lanquage of the source and the desired output, respectively (in the example, from French to English). If the source argument is not specified, Google will try to guess the language of the source. If the target argument is not specified, the default is English. The format argument can be used to specify whether the source is a plain text document or an HTML document.

1.2.1 Spanish Documents

The gl_translate() function can be used on all Spanish “Lessons Learned” parts. To that end, we create an empty list that can be filled with the translated texts. We loop over all the texts to translate and do not forget to monitor how many characters were translated so that the 500,000 character limit is not exceeded.

load("../data/pcr_reports_lessons_spanish.rda")

pcr_reports_lessons_spanish


# Look whether some documents were already translated
if(file.exists("../data/reports_translated_en.rda")){
  load("../data/reports_translated_en.rda")
  # Some texts were already translated. We need to translate the remaining, if any
  # Let us define the index where the first non-translated document is located
  i_start <- which(sapply(reports_translated_en, length) == 0)[1]
  # (i_start will be equal to NA is all documents are translated)
}else{
  reports_translated_en <- vector(mode="list", length = nrow(pcr_reports_lessons_spanish))
  i_start <- 1
}


if(!is.na(i_start)){
  # If some texts are still to be translated
  pb <- txtProgressBar(min=1, max=nrow(pcr_reports_lessons_spanish), style = 3)
  for(i in i_start:nrow(pcr_reports_lessons_spanish)){
    text_current <- pcr_reports_lessons_spanish$lessons_learned[i]
    # Translate from Spanish to English using Google Translate API
    text_current_en <- googleLanguageR::gl_translate(text_current, target = "en", format = "text", source = "es")
    reports_translated_en[[i]] <- text_current_en
    setTxtProgressBar(pb, i)
  }
  save(reports_translated_en, file = "../data/reports_translated_en.rda")
  # Add the ID
  for(i in 1:length(reports_translated_en)){
    reports_translated_en[[i]] <- 
      reports_translated_en[[i]] %>% mutate(ID = pcr_reports_lessons_spanish$ID[i])
  }
  
  pcr_reports_lessons_spanish_translated <- 
    pcr_reports_lessons_spanish %>% 
    left_join(
      reports_translated_en %>% bind_rows() %>% 
        select(ID, translated_text = translatedText)
    )
  
  save(pcr_reports_lessons_spanish_translated, file = "../data/pcr_reports_lessons_spanish_translated.rda")
}

  # Let us define the index where the first non-translated document is located

if(!is.na(i_start)){
  # If some texts are still to be translated
  pb <- txtProgressBar(min=1, max=nrow(pcr_reports_lessons_french), style = 3)
  
  # Monitor the number of characters to translate not to go over the 500,000 daily limiy
  nb_chars <- 0
  
  for(i in i_start:nrow(pcr_reports_lessons_french)){
    text_current <- pcr_reports_lessons_french$lessons_learned[i]
    nb_chars <- nb_chars + str_length(text_current)
    if(nb_chars <= 500000){
      # Translate from French to English using Google Translate API
      text_current_en <- googleLanguageR::gl_translate(text_current, target = "en", format = "text", source = "fr")
      reports_translated_en[[i]] <- text_current_en
      setTxtProgressBar(pb, i)
    }else{
      stop("Daily Limit Reached. Try again tomorrow with i=", i)
    }
  }
  
  save(reports_translated_en, file = "../data/reports_fr_translated_en.rda")
  
  
  # Add the ID
  for(i in 1:length(reports_translated_en)){
    reports_translated_en[[i]] <- 
      reports_translated_en[[i]] %>% mutate(ID = pcr_reports_lessons_french$ID[i])
  }
  
  pcr_reports_lessons_french_translated <- 
    pcr_reports_lessons_french %>%

        select(ID, translated_text = translatedText)
    )

}

2.2 Lessons Learned

Let us turn to the lessons learned sections of the reports. First, we should remove the punctuation characters from the text and convert all words to lower case:

pcr_lessons_learned <- 
  pcr_lessons_learned %>% 
  mutate(lessons_learned_clean = 
           lessons_learned %>%
           str_remove_all("[[:punct:]]") %>% 
           str_remove_all("[[:digit:]]") %>% 
           str_remove_all("\n") %>% 
           str_trim() %>% 
           str_remove_all("[[:space:]]{2,}") %>% 
           str_to_lower())

Let us count how many characters and how many words are in the section “Lessons Learned” of each report:

pcr_lessons_learned <- 
  pcr_lessons_learned %>% 
  mutate(no_chars = str_length(lessons_learned_clean),
         no_words = str_count(lessons_learned_clean, "\\S+"))
